This was a delightfully unique way to serve regular old pork chops. As the other reviewer noted, it would be best to carmelize the onions first (which I did not) to give it a richer flavor. I used a regular apple and a granny smith probably would be better. But, I followed the directions exactly and it was still very good. I will make this again. Oh, I did use dried basil instead of marjoram since I did not have that spice on hand.

Rating: 3
Simply fantastic!!! The sauce is to die for! After reading the reviews and the cooking method, I made a few changes: used 1.5 Walla Walla onions and carmelized until deep golden brown; then added 2 coarsely diced Granny Smith apples and the garlic and continued to saute to a deep rich brown; deglazed the pan with the wine; added the chicken broth and simmered until reduced by half; stirred in honey dijon, the herbs, curry powder, salt/pepper and the cream and continued to simmer for a few minutes until reduced and nicely thickened. The resulting marmalade-like sauce had a luscious colour. Made the day before so the flavours could marry/deepen, then reheated. This sauce was a real taste treat that beautifully complemented a centre-cut, Frenched, pork rack, slowly cooked on the gas barbecue rotisserie and then sliced into chops. This is a yummy dish that is company worthy, yet so easy to prepare. I think the key to the sauce is to brown the onions/apples thoroughly, rather than following the recipe directions which I feel would result in a very insipid flavour and an anemic colour. Give it a try, you will not be disappointed!

